        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>[Down]</placeName>
                    <date>Wednesday</date>
                    <salute>Dear Innes</salute>  
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I strongly recommend you to read enclosed beginning at p. 38 to 91.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Von Siebold is about the most careful &amp; profound naturalist in Europe.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I have found in this Book some facts, such as I was enquiring from you in regard to Bees.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Ever yours | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.3 in this Book] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated from the reference to Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold’s work on parthenogenesis (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7182.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Siebold 1856</ref>), an English translation of which (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7183.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Siebold 1857</ref>) was published between 31 January and 16 February 1857 (<hi rend="italic">Publishers’ Circular</hi>, 16 February 1857, p. 94). CD’s copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7183.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Siebold 1857</ref> is in the Darwin Library–CUL.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The page numbers refer to the chapter in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7183.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Siebold 1857</ref> entitled ‘True parthenogenesis in the honey bee’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Siebold had been appointed <hi rend="italic">Ordinarius</hi> professor of zoology and comparative anatomy at the University of Munich in 1853. He was noted for his detailed microscopical researches on invertebrates.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD cited <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7183.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Siebold 1857</ref> in his discussion of the two varieties of the common hive-bee in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref>, p. 372 n. 5.</note>
        </div>        
            
